top : real time system information, including CPU, memory and process usage
df -h : Checks disk space usage 
free -h : memory usage, including free, used and swap memory
vmstat : system processes, memory, paging, blockid, traps, and CPU activity
iostat : CPU and I/O statics

* File Management :
ls :  directory listing
ls -la : list files with details
grep pattern file : searches for a specific pattern within a file
cp source_file target_file : This copies the entire file (not just the content) 
cat source_file > target_file : This overwrites the target_file with the content of source_file
cat source_file >> target_file : To append the content instead of overwriting
mkdir yogesh : creates a directory yogesh 
cd yogesh : change directory to yogesh
cd : change to home directory
pwd : shows current working directory
cat file_name : displays the content of the file
touch file_name : create or update a file


* File Management commands :-

->  pwd : This command is used to displays the present working directory

-> mkdir : This command is used to create a new directory

-> touch : This command is used to creates an empty file
  
-> ls : This command is used to listing content of a directory

-> ls -al : This command is used to formatted listing with hidden files

-> ls -lt : This command is used to sorting the formatted listing by time modification

-> cd : This command is used to change current directory

-> sudo : This command is used to execute a command with superuser privileges

-> chmod : This command will give the user permission to read,write and execute a file

-> history : This command is used to display the previously executed commands

-> top : This command is used to monitor real-time system resource usage, including CPU, memory and process activity

  
